INSERT INTO `_WPI_posts` VALUES (179,6,'2019-09-04 06:52:40','2019-09-04 06:52:40','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Originally posted September 14, 2018 on my personal blog.</em> <em>This was during my time as a legal intern for Nevada Legal Services, a nonprofit that services those under the poverty line in Las Vegas, Nevada</em>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For work, I had to travel an hour out of Las Vegas to the small city of Pahrump, Nevada to interview a small group of homeless people. To give you an idea of Pahrump, the Mayor owns a brothel and calls himself the \"Trump of Pahrump.\" The reason the drive was warranted was because the local Nye County Sheriff\'s Deputies raided a local homeless encampment call \"The Hill\" consisting of around 40-50 people in abandoned land. As expected, it is located up a desert dirt hill composed of RV\'s, tents, cars, and trailers. The nonprofit I volunteer for was listening to their stories and formalizing them into some formal action to aid this community.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The camp itself is around 7-8 years old, but this was not their first time being forced out of the land. Five years ago, the camp was threatened to be bulldozed by developers, but the then residents were just warned to move further back. The land was believed to be property of the Bureau of Land Management, which is an agency that handles and auctions land on the behalf of the federal government. It\'s pretty common practice, especially in Nevada where much land is unsold or underdeveloped outside of the major cities. After the initial incident, there has not been a single warning or notice, but that changed when the owner finally visited his property. According to one resident, an officer told him that the landowner almost threw up at the sight of the camp. The Police were summoned shortly after.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The actual eviction took place on September 12, 2018. Residents vary on the time, but most believe it occurred around 10:00 AM. Nye County Sheriffs Deputies rolled into the camp blaring sirens to the surprise of many residents. Some were still sleeping, but most were awakened by the aggressive verbal and physical warnings to leave within 15 minutes or risk being arrested for trespassing. Before the incident, Nye County Police have been through the camp before, but mostly to find certain persons of interests. In some incidents, the residents themselves have even called police to handle domestic disputes. No officer ever mentioned trespassing before.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The residents I met are not easy to generalize. Granted, they were all white, but they came from everywhere. Some were living around the Nye County area for years before finding this community. One woman is from Wisconsin fleeing from an abusive domestic violence situation. A young but wilting couple were from Hurricane Harvey trying to find a place with no hurricanes. They had lost everything just a month prior, and an older Hill . resident gave the unlucky couple her trailer to live in before passing on. One older resident is a veteran whose insufficient VA checks could never cover rent in any of the surrounding areas. Some admitted mental health issues that prevented working. Most residents came across bad luck in life, but all were grateful for The Hill.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the eyes of some, the Hill has granted some unparalleled access to society\'s most vulnerable including a local domestic violence shelter, a local Pahrump church, homeless coalitions, and nonprofits. Churches often come up to give clothes, food, water, and other necessities. Drug use does occur in \"The Hill,\" but only privately within private confines. The only real issue might be when someone gets a little too drunk, but I don\'t think that\'s an income-exclusive problem. Even in facing eviction, groups within the Hill are trying to stay together to pool resources and figure out the next steps.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One story demonstrating the importance of this community to some was from the lady from Wisconsin. While her husband was away for work, she was awakened, choked and raped by some visiting members of the camp. When other members of the camp found out, they armed themselves and walked these two visitors out of the camp down the hill. Women and men were separating the victim from the rapists all along the road to ensure their departure. After that incident, the young lady from Wisconsin sees the community as family. She recently discovered brain cancer tragically to accompany her 7-month pregnancy, and the Hill is the only thing holding her together. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The community is now scattered drifting between couches, hiding in other abandoned lots, or still trying to find their next option. Most residents just didn\'t have enough time to grab everything. Trailers and RVs full of personal belongings like priceless guitars, solar panels, and perishable foods are still up there sparsely patrolled by police. Everyone I talked to just wants more time to grab the rest of their things and their homes. Granted, the residents were trespassing on land that was abandoned for years, but this is from the conditions that we have created as a society. We have ignored our most vulnerable people. For creating their own opportunity in the face of misfortune, we punish them with inhumane treatment that none of us would ever have to face. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In Nevada, a landlord is required to deliver a Five-Day Notice to Pay Rent or Quit to the tenant. If there is no lease agreement, Nevada law requires a thirty-day \"no cause\" notice for the tenant to leave. For whatever crimes the Hill residents may have committed, our tax dollars, elected politicians, and our reinforced values all perpetuate the very conditions to those that least deserve it. If they are guilty, we are as well. What I would advocate for is a humane alternative for the Hill residents to transition into, if not possible then, at least a humane amount of time to move their belongings that anyone would receive. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Khailil Gibran famously wrote:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"And if any of you would punish in the name of righteousness and lay the ax unto the evil tree, let him see to its roots;<br>And verily he will find the roots of the good and the bad, the fruitful and the fruitless, all entwined together in the silent heart of the earth.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Edit: Nye County listened to their stories, but despite all efforts, the residents were ultimately evicted. Many forced into Las Vegas shelters that were already overcrowded. </em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','City Upon the Hill','','inherit','closed','closed','','176-revision-v1','','','2019-09-04 06:52:40','2019-09-04 06:52:40','',176,'http://born-great.local/2019/09/04/176-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0);
